  "prompt": "U.S. Immigration: Can an H1-B visa be extended by future employers beyond 6 years based on an approved I-140 through the previous employer?",
  "response": "Yes, a future employer can extend your H-1B visa beyond the standard six-year limit based on an approved I-140 petition from a previous employer. This extension is possible under the provisions of the **American Competitiveness in the Twenty-First Century Act (AC21)**. Here's how it works and the conditions that apply:\n\n### **Understanding the H-1B Six-Year Limit**\n- **Standard Duration:** The H-1B visa is typically granted for an initial period of up to three years, with the possibility of a one-time extension for an additional three years, totaling a maximum of six years.\n  \n### **Extensions Beyond Six Years**\n- **AC21 Section 106(a) and (b):** This section allows H-1B holders to extend their stay beyond six years if they meet certain criteria related to the employment-based green card process.\n  \n### **Criteria for Extension Beyond Six Years**\n\n1. **Approved I-140 Petition:**\n   - **Requirement:** You must have an approved I-140 Immigrant Petition for Alien Worker from a previous employer.\n   - **Benefit:** An approved I-140 indicates that you are eligible for an employment-based green card, which is a key factor in extending your H-1B status beyond six years.\n\n2. **Change of Employer:**\n   - **Portability:** Under AC21, you can change employers and still use the approved I-140 from your previous employer to extend your H-1B status.\n   - **Same or Similar Occupational Classification:** The new job with the future employer must be in the same or a similar occupational classification as the job for which the I-140 was approved.\n\n3. **Validity of the I-140:**\n   - **Current Status:** The I-140 must remain valid and unrevoked. If your original employer withdraws the I-140 before you file for Adjustment of Status (I-485), it could jeopardize your ability to extend beyond six years.\n   - **Portability Provisions:** If you change employers after your I-140 is approved and before it is revoked, you may still be able to use it for extensions under certain \"portability\" rules.\n\n4. **Filing the Extension:**\n   - **Timelines:** It's advisable to file for the H-1B extension as early as possible to avoid gaps in employment authorization.\n   - **Documentation:** Ensure that you provide all necessary documentation, including proof of the approved I-140 and evidence that the new position is in the same or a similar occupational classification.\n\n### **Practical Steps for Extending H-1B with a New Employer**\n\n1. **Secure a Job Offer:** Obtain a job offer from a future employer willing to sponsor your H-1B extension.\n2. **File a New H-1B Petition:** The future employer must file a new H-1B petition on your behalf, referencing the approved I-140.\n3. **Demonstrate Eligibility:** Provide evidence that the approved I-140 is still valid and that the new role aligns with the classification of the approved petition.\n4. **Await Approval:** Once the extension is approved, you can continue working beyond the six-year limit under the extended H-1B status.\n\n### **Additional Considerations**\n\n- **Green Card Process:** Extending your H-1B beyond six years is typically a stopgap measure while awaiting the final steps of the green card process, such as filing the Adjustment of Status (I-485).\n- **Consult an Immigration Attorney:** Given the complexities of immigration law, it's highly recommended to consult with an experienced immigration attorney to navigate your specific situation successfully.\n\n### **Summary**\nIn summary, having an approved I-140 petition from a previous employer does provide a pathway to extend your H-1B visa beyond six years with a new employer. However, this is contingent upon meeting specific criteria, including the validity of the I-140, the similarity of the new job to the original position, and timely filing of the necessary petitions. Proper planning and legal guidance are essential to ensure compliance with all immigration regulations.",
